    "content_hash": "sha256:e82afb1e033c5bb1feb2e18d699e670b6e4f487e91007cf933788127ef2e51cb",
    "summary": "The Benin Bronzes refer to the extraordinary corpus of brass and bronze sculptures, plaques, and ceremonial objects produced by the artists of the Kingdom of Benin (in modern-day Nigeria) from roughly the 13th century onward, representing one of the most sophisticated metalworking traditions in human history. The Edo-speaking Benin Kingdom, centered on the royal city of Benin (Benin City), developed a highly organized guild system of court artists — the igun-eronmwon — who worked exclusively for the Oba (king) producing commemorative plaques, royal heads, figurines, and ceremonial objects in lost-wax (cire-perdue) bronze casting of remarkable technical mastery. The royal palace walls were lined with rectangular brass plaques depicting court scenes, military campaigns, and ritual ceremonies, creating a visual archive of Benin history that had no parallel in sub-Saharan Africa.\n\nThe tradition's origins are traced to the legendary bronzesmith Iguegha, who was sent from Ife — the Yoruba spiritual capital — to teach the craft to Benin's artisans around the 13th century, connecting Benin bronze-casting to the earlier Ife tradition of naturalistic brass heads. By the 15th century, when Portuguese traders first arrived in Benin (around 1485), the kingdom was producing work of stunning quality: the famous Benin Heads — idealized portrait sculptures of obas and queen mothers — displayed a naturalism and technical sophistication that European visitors found astonishing. The bronzes served not merely as art but as instruments of royal legitimacy, ancestor veneration, and political communication. The bulk of surviving Benin Bronzes were seized by a British punitive expedition in 1897 and dispersed to museums worldwide, sparking one of modern history's most prominent cultural repatriation debates.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benin_Bronzes",
